<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-1101] bytebuffer length calculation in TBinaryProtocol writeBinary</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-1101</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;In TBinaryProtocol writeBinary, the length calculation appears incorrect:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  length = bin.limit() - bin.position() - bin.arrayOffset();&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This subtraction of arrayOffset can cause a negative length on a sliced buffer. For example:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  ByteBuffer b = ByteBuffer.allocate(15);&lt;br/&gt;
  b.put(&quot;1234567890&quot;.getBytes());&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;  ByteBuffer b2 = b.slice();&lt;br/&gt;
  b2.put(&quot;testx&quot;.getBytes());&lt;br/&gt;
  b2.rewind();&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So b2&apos;s length is lim-pos-offset = 5-0-10 = -5.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I believe we just want lim-pos.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
